Something's a bit messed up with this PR (the diff is 90k lines). Maybe merge master? Or if that doesn't work, ask on Zulip.
I have strain injuries to both wrists, hence must not type much. Please apologise the poor spelling, vague indications and general conciseness.
Is this not already [Con.instCompleteLattice](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/GroupTheory/Congruence/Defs.html#Con.instCompleteLattice) ?
you're right, it's fixed now! Looks like this material had been moved to Congrence/Defs while I was working on this PR, and I didn't fully update everything

```suggestion
theorem comap_conGen_of_bijective {M N : Type*} [Mul M] [Mul N] (f : M  N)
```
~~I am surprised you need bijectivity here. I would expect this be true when `f` is not ...~~ Nevermind I am being silly
Can you prove an inequality one way using only injectivity/surjectivity?

Neat idea! I can prove one inequality without either, and then the other inequality requires bijectivity. I've separated out the inequality which doesn't require either as conGen_le_comap; but when I use it for the second half of comap_conGen_of_Bijective, it only unifies when I use "apply", not "exact" --
"show term" produces an "exact" statement that won't work. Do you have any idea what's happening?
That seems... weird. I would investigate but it's time for me to go home for the day. Maybe bring it up on Zulip

Thanks! I think I might've figured it out.

I think it's because of the implicit arguments for the instance of LE on Con
 x y, c x y  d x y

(which here should be a and b)

Lean won't match them correctly with "exact"; it searches harder with "apply"

If I simply give them to "exact", by using @ to specify the implicit arguments as well, that works too

And even better, if I use a fact about LE to avoid using ext (and thus fussing about with the a and b), everything clicks into place just right

Thanks for pointing out that the two directions should be separate - it makes the code much nicer!

Here are a few uses of dot notation that might or might not work
```suggestion
  exact ConGen.Rel.rec (fun x y h  ConGen.Rel.of (f x) (f y) h) (fun x  .refl (f x))
```

```suggestion
    (fun _  .symm) (fun _ _  .trans) (fun {w x y z} _ _ h1 h2 
```

```suggestion
    (h1.mul h2))) h
```

```suggestion
theorem le_comap_conGen {M N : Type*} [Mul M] [Mul N] (f : M  N)
```
seems like a more discoverable name (it's like `comap_conGen`, but one-sided)

```suggestion
theorem comap_conGen_of_bijective {M N : Type*} [Mul M] [Mul N] (f : M  N)
```

```suggestion
noncomputable def comapQuotientEquivOfSurj (c : Con M) (f : N * M) (hf : Function.Surjective f) :
```

```suggestion
/-- If `e : M * N` is surjective then `(c.comap e).Quotient * c.Quotient` with `c : Con N`. -/
```
Same below
done!

```suggestion
@[to_additive (attr := simp)]
```
same below
added!

```suggestion
/-- This version infers the surjectivity of the function from a MulEquiv function -/
@[to_additive (attr := simp) "Copy edocstring here"]
lemma comapQuotientEquivOfSurj_symm_mk' (c : Con M) (f : N * M) (x : N) :
```
copied!

```suggestion
      (comapQuotientEquivOfSurj c f f.surjective)) f x) = x :=
```

Happy to make the change! Could you explain what's happening here so I know for the future? 

I'd thought hypotheses beyond the first line were indented twice (2 tabs, or 4 spaces), and then the proof itself begins at one indent (1 tab, or 2 spaces). 

Would this mean 
(A) first line is not indented, second line with hypotheses is indented twice, third line is indented 3 times, fourth 4 times, etc?

(B) first line is not indented, all further lines with hypotheses are indented twice, but this one gets an extra indent to show the grouping of the parentheses? (basically since we're splitting up the parenthesized 
```
(@MulEquiv.symm (Con.Quotient (comap f _ c)) _ _ _
    (comapQuotientEquivOfSurj c f f.surjective))
```

trying to make it multiple choice to reduce typing for you :)
thanks for the thought. Basically A, except that later lines can be less indented than what A says depending on hestructure of the expression
